VEO 3 Video Prompt Generator GPT 
Builder: Rodrigo Espinosa Quinteros
Type: Custom GPT (ChatGPT)
Status: Live deployment
Language: Bilingual (Spanish input → English JSON output)
Domain: AI Video Generation, Creative Production

Overview
A specialized GPT that transforms a creative brief written in Spanish or English into
a valid, production-ready JSON prompt for VEO 3 via Google Flow. The GPT bridges the
gap between a non-technical creative brief and the structured technical format that
AI video generation models require to produce consistent, high-quality output.
The design philosophy: zero friction between creative intent and technical execution.
The user thinks in creative terms (objective, audience, message, style); the GPT thinks
in production terms (composition, cinematography, audio parameters, color palette).

Architecture
Single-Module, Single-Output Design
Unlike multi-module GPTs, this system has one job: receive a brief, fill a JSON
template, output the JSON. No routing, no branching flows, no conversation history
required. The entire value is in the transformation logic — the rules that govern
how a vague creative input becomes a precise technical specification.
User input: "Genera mi prompt JSON"
→ GPT requests structured brief (9 fields)
→ User provides brief in Spanish or English
→ GPT generates single valid JSON object
→ Output: ready-to-paste VEO 3 prompt
Brief-to-JSON Transformation Rules
The system prompt encodes a complete set of inference and formatting rules that govern
every field in the output:
Language handling:

All JSON fields output in English
Exception: dialogue.line, audio.lyrics, and voiceover text stay in Spanish,
exactly as provided by the user — preserving phonetics and cultural nuance for
AI audio generation

Intelligent defaults:

Platform: Instagram Reels (9:16 vertical) if not specified
Duration: 8–15 seconds if not specified
Frame rate: always "30fps" — locked, never inferred
Color palette: brand gradient system if not specified (blue-to-orange, green-to-blue,
white base)

No empty fields policy:
Every field in the JSON must have a value. If the user's brief doesn't supply a
specific detail, the GPT infers it from the objective, audience, platform, and style
context. This is a critical design decision — empty or null fields cause VEO 3 to
fall back to defaults that may not match creative intent.

JSON Template Structure
The output follows a fixed 12-section schema:
shot          → composition, camera motion, frame rate, film grain
subject       → description, wardrobe
scene         → location, time of day, environment
visual_details → action, props
cinematography → lighting, tone
audio         → ambient, lyrics, vocal style (delivery/flow/phrasing/texture),
                voice tone, tempo, rhythm
color_palette → brand-aligned or brief-specified
dialogue      → character, line (in Spanish), subtitles
The schema is designed around VEO 3's generation parameters — each field maps directly
to a dimension the model uses to control visual and audio output.

Tone Presets
Two predefined style presets can be invoked by name, automatically populating the
cinematography fields:
Cinematic clean:
Soft balanced lighting, stable camera, subtle depth of field, high clarity, polished
cinematic look — suited for brand, product, and corporate content.
Handmade stop-motion:
Fine organic grain, natural daylight, handcrafted textures, frame-by-frame motion feel
— suited for artisan brands, food, lifestyle, and creative content.
Presets reduce the cognitive load of specifying technical cinematography parameters for
users who think in aesthetic terms rather than production terms.

Brief Intake Structure
The GPT collects 9 fields before generating output:
FieldPurposeVideo objectiveDrives tone, pacing, and CTA placementAudience & platform (ratio) Determines format defaults and visual complexityKey messageAnchors dialogue, on-screen text, and audio directionTarget durationConstrains scene count and pacingVisual style or presetPopulates cinematography and tone fieldsCall to actionInforms final scene compositionVoiceover / dialogue (exact Spanish text)Preserved verbatim in outputRestrictions (logos, colors, no-brand rules)Applied as constraints across all fieldsAdditional notesCatches edge cases and creative preferences
Key design decision: The brief is collected as a structured form, not a free-form
conversation. This produces consistently parseable inputs that map cleanly to JSON
fields, reducing generation errors and hallucinated values.

Output Design
Single object, no explanation. The GPT outputs only the JSON — no preamble, no
commentary, no follow-up questions. This is intentional: the output is designed to be
copied directly into Flow without editing. Any surrounding text would add friction to
the production workflow.
On-screen text constraint: Text overlays are limited to 25 characters per scene,
matching VEO 3's optimal rendering range for legibility at mobile scale.

Key Takeaways

Bilingual field-level control (English structure, Spanish dialogue/lyrics) is a
nuanced pattern for GPTs that serve Spanish-speaking markets but interface with
English-language AI tools. Language rules need to be field-specific, not
document-wide.
No empty fields as a hard rule shifts the intelligence burden from the user to
the GPT. Inference from context (objective + audience + platform) produces better
results than leaving fields blank or asking follow-up questions.
Structured brief intake (fixed fields, not free-form) is more reliable than
conversational brief extraction for technical output tasks. It reduces ambiguity
and produces inputs that map predictably to output fields.
Tone presets as UX layer abstract technical parameters behind creative vocabulary.
Users who don't know what "depth of field" means can still specify "cinematic clean"
and get a properly configured cinematography block.
Output-only design (no explanation, no commentary) is the right choice when the
deliverable is machine-readable and the user's next action is copy-paste into another
tool. Explanatory text adds noise, not value.
